<br>
Quick Announcement:<br>
If you hear me talking about my calculation for rain aggro, I just noticed something odd! In my intersects based calculation of rain aggro, I came up with a figure of 41.5% aggro for a rain. Now, what's the significance of this? Well, I'll tell you:<br>
R = Rain Wave Damage<br>
SCS = .8, the scs modifier for you<br>
R/(3R*.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  = 41.67%! (41 2/3 actually, /wave decimal)<br>
I was just poking through lucy and noticed the base1 of the spell was -850, which is what many believe determines the base aggro of a nuke. What's this mean to me? Well, pesonally I calculated this from 4 different wizards, including myself... and came to roughly 41.5% on every case. I'd think that rains are effected by SCS as I found the 41.5% figure with a wizard who lacked the SCS line of spells. However it counts, lucy indicates that the base aggro of the spell may be -850... it's either 1/3 of 41.5% aggro for a rain. I lean to the latter figure from experience but the 1/3 is clean from lucy- but I don't know how the aggro mechanic works for rains.<br>
<br>
Heavy Hitters - SOS, AT, SOM<br>
Advantages: These spells produce the raw damage, and fast- lots of it.<br>
Disadvantages: No lowered aggro! If resisted, produces the same aggro as if it wasn't resisted - which can be too often in the case of these nukes.<br>
Uses: Especially useful when a high aggro tank, such as a Paladin, is aggroing your target hard. Rings that produce multiple targets that need your highest burst dps allow you to overcome the aggro problem and do the fastest dmg possible.<br>
special note: the Shock of Magic spell, in truth, is only good for showing off extremely rare 7k+ crits. Just hearing the &quot;woot!&quot; from the observers is worth it - sometimes. The faster speed of damage means that, when not resisted, it gives you more 'free time' with which to conc. That is, in order to do the same damage, it takes less time- the spare time can add up to concs which increases your aggro limit.<br>
Note- SOM is crit-candy.<br>
<br>
Draughts - Dr:Ro, Dr:E'c, (D:Thunder)<br>
Advantages: Lower resist rate and smaller damage chunk allows for earlier nuking. The lower resist means that the draught produces less aggro when a SOS would have been resisted.<br>
Disadvantage: nonetheless has standard aggro. the mana ratio is lower on this(long fights, see 'luclin'!), the damage speed is lower.<br>
Uses: Against mobs with higher resists, these are very valuable. resists lower your dmg speed and dmg ration. The smaller hit makes the aggro easier to manage.<br>
Note: Draught of Thunder has a much higher aggro output due to its stun component. It works on players in pvp, but players generally have too much MR for it.<br>
<br>
Lure - Thunder, Ro, Ice<br>
Advantages: Extremely Hard to resist<br>
Disadvantages: low damage speed, low ratio.<br>
Uses: on some(especially older) content, lures are needed to damage the mob effectively due to huge resists.<br>
Note: Lure of Ice, due to iceflame, produces lessened aggro for the dmg it can do.<br>
<br>
Tears: Arlyxir, Ro, Marr<br>
Advantages: Rains do their damage while producing somewhere between 1/3 - 41.6% of the aggro that would correspond to their damage. With the hard cap resist, the ratios are somewhat similar to their corresponding nuke. <br>
Disadvantages: CC'd mobs by whatever you're nuking will block the rain AE and hit the extra mob. Marr/Ro have modest resist checks, and Aryxil a bad dmg/time ratio. The way rains work is a bit buggy, haste focus items can cause the rains to lose waves until re-equipped(not too big), and some mobs don't even take the rain damage.<br>
Uses: Rains are like a conc and a nuke - in one! Heck, make that two a:concs- which would take 8.5 sec(if no pants). When limited by aggro, the value is obvious. That's a really fast way to make a portion of your damage aggro free(what we conc for)... in a way sueprior to the concs themselves.<br>
<br>
note: what's this &quot;deaggro&quot; thing? It's what I call the aggro-free damage a wizard does in a fight. A conc? -400 aggro, meaning 400pts free, of 94/sec(188/sec pants). I has something significant to say, though. The tears of marr spell without a crit has a deaggro rate between 232 and 203. Like conc but does damage! The spell, however, increases your aggro despite this 'deaggro' thing - the dmg rate is greater than the free dmg.<br>
<br>
ISOS/DOI:<br>
Advantages: 38.7aggro/sec is the 'deaggro rating' I give isos. That makes it a good bit superior, when not resisted, to other DDs(which do not have any innate deaggo-action). They're also very efficient.<br>
Disadvantages: DOI/ISOS are plagued by the resist kremlin, too. No -50 check is available on these nukes, so they become less useful where the ice resists ramp up.<br>
Uses: Anywhere efficiency is needed, so, too, shall DOI/ISOS be useful. In faster fights, they can produce high damage with the extra ~half-conc power. <br>
<br>
If anyone wishes to challenge my opinion on this matter and say that one nuke or the other is always superior, I am interested in this assertation. I do not think this is the case. Based upon my opinion, I recommend wizards survey the full arsenal of their spells and use the precise one that best fits the situation.<br>
<br>
It's useful to take advantage of the intricacies of your class. Granted, many people who have had the strange luck of achieving level 65 nonetheless think that wizards do nothing but press a nuke button repeatedly(one, who is thankfully not a member of my guild, thought that the spellbutton for SOS was purple - 65 war), and associate Strike of Solusek almost exclusively as the 'wizard nuke' especially when it is a spell that, in truth, is inferior in most applications than similar spells. <br>
<br>
-thanks for reading the book! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=urgetakildaogur>Urgetakil da Ogur</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://members.aol.com/_ht_a/jordanzone/ff2/gifs/cecil.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/18/03 1:01:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25467.topic&index=70>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fohguild.org/forums/avatar.php?userid=595&dateline=1020585489 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ~</span><hr size=1> The other night we got SoS for one of our wizards right before engaging seru...i swear i nearly pissed my pants...first SoS on seru...YOU WILL NOT EVADE ME EVULL!! Evull has been slain by Lord Inquisitor Seru. I laughed so hard i was crying. The rest of the wizards were siting back draughting and concussioning. This was also the day that aggro was all fugged and crits were giving a little too much aggro so that might have played some part in his demise. When i played my wiz i always prefered to draught, concussion, draught s'more toss in the occassional Sunstrike and such (gave my wiz to a friend before PoP came out)<br>
